const MOD = 1e9 + 7

function createSortedArray(instructions) {
    let nums = new Set();
    let cost = 0;

    for (let i of instructions) {
        nums.add(i);
        let sortedNums = Array.from(nums).sort((a, b) => a - b);
        let less_than = sortedNums.filter(x => x < i).length;
        let greater_than = sortedNums.filter(x => x > i).length;
        cost = (cost + Math.min(less_than, greater_than)) % MOD;
        nums = new Set(sortedNums);
    }

    return cost;
}
```

    First, initialize a container `s` and `cost` variable to store elements and cost. Iterate through each element in ‘instructions’. For each element, calculate the count of elements less than and greater than the current element in the container. Add minimum of the counts to the `cost` and apply modulo 1e9 + 7 to the cost. Finally, insert the element into the container. After the iteration, return the total `cost`.

Note that for higher efficiency, we use specific data structures with built-in functionality, such as C++'s `multiset` or Python's `SortedList`, so time complexity is kept at O(N * log(N)).

